                   SECTION 1 - BASIC NETWORKING

WHAT IS A LAN?

A LAN is an acronym for Local Area Network.  A local area
network is a group of computers that are connected by
some source, be it wire, fiber, or radio waves.  A
typical LAN consists of a server, which houses the NOS
(network operating system), the physical connections to
the computers, and the clients or workstations.

WHAT DOES A LAN PROVIDE?

The most fundamental use of any LAN is to provide a means
to share information and resources.  Information can be
shared via common disk drives or access to other user's
disk drives.  Hardware such as printers, faxes, CD-ROMS,
etc. are all examples of resources that can be maximized
by sharing them among users.

TYPES OF LANS

It's possible that three types of LANs can be defined:

1)  Basic
2)  Peer-to-peer
3)  Advanced

Basic usually provides a connection of a computer to
other computers, such as other LANs or mainframes.  Peer-
to-peer networks offer the ability to share workstation
devices such as printers, and access disk drives on other
workstations.  Advanced networks offer the most feature
intensive type of network, with centralized file sharing
and storage, as well as resource utilization.

HOW DO I PLAN A LAN?

Perhaps the most important issue in planning for a LAN is
to keep in mind the growth of your organization.  Some
growth in most organizations is inevitable, in many,
desired.  Planning for a LAN that only meets your needs
today is self-defeating, in that you will have management
and usage headaches if you outgrow the LAN.  Keep in mind
however, that staged implementations of a LAN are fine,
and provide a means to spread the cost over several
months/years, depending on the situation at your site.  A
phased implementation plan also allows you to grow with
the LAN, adding new components and parts as you master
the old ones.

Regardless of the methods used for installing a LAN at
your site, planning must incorporate as a minimum, the
following components:

     1)  Type of existing equipment
     2)  Current applications
     3)  Current hardware and software usage
     4)  Goals of the LAN
     5)  Budget
     6)  Training
     7)  Support

Additionally, depending on the situation, you may need to
also consider:

     1)   Connections to other LAN systems 
     2)   Availability of hardware/software
     3)   Any local standards (i.e., in a college/large
          corporation environment)
     4)   Availability of technical assistance

COMMON NETWORKING TERMS

The following list of terms is not meant to be inclusive
or even exhaustive.  It is simply a quick compilation of
terms that a person entering the field of LANs might be
exposed to.

 Appletalk:        The protocol developed by Apple
                   Computer to implement file and
                   resource sharing between Macintosh
                   computers.
 
 AUI:              "Attachment Unit Interface" - a type
                   of connection between devices.

 Backbone:         A data highway used to transfer
                   information between remote
                   sites/locations.

 Banyan VINES:     Also known simply as "VINES", one of
                   several NOS's providing advanced
                   networking capabilities.

 BNC Connector:    "Bayonet Neill-Concelman connector" -
                   a connection type used on coaxial
                   cable.

 Bridge:           A relay which sends data from one
                   data link (location) to another data
                   link (location).  A bridge usually
                   buffers the data, and allows hardware
                   above the bridge to see only one
                   device.  A bridge may also be used to
                   secure an area of the LAN from sets
                   of users.

 Coaxial Cable:    Any one of several types of cable for
                   electronic communications.
 
 Concentrator:     A piece of equipment that gives
                   interconnection capabilities to
                   people on a network, such as to
                   access to the server.

 DECnet:           Trade name of the family of
                   networking products from Digital
                   Equipment Corporation.  One of
                   several NOS's providing advanced
                   networking capabilities.

 E-Mail:           "Electronic Mail" - any one of
                   numerous software packages that allow
                   a user in one location to send
                   electronic messages across a
                   connecting medium to a user in
                   another location.

 Ethernet:         A LAN protocol 

 FDDI:              "Fiber Data Distribution Interface"
                   - A LAN protocol for the transmission
                   of information on a network.
 
 Fiber:            "Optical fiber" - a long, narrow,
                   flexible piece of glass, used for
                   high-speed communications.

 FTP               "File Transfer Protocol" - A protocol
                   used to copy files from one computer
                   to another.

 Gateway:          A relay of sorts, that "attaches" one
                   network to another network.  (Often
                   used in conjunction with the transfer
                   of electronic mail).

 Hub:              A piece of equipment that gives
                   interconnection capabilities to
                   people on a network, such as to
                   access to the server.

 IP:               A "generic" protocol on which many
                   specific data transmission schemes
                   have been based.

 IPX:              The network protocol used by Novell
 
 MAU:              "Media Adaptor Unit" - a device for
                   attaching a workstation to a  LAN
                   segment for communication within the
                   LAN.

 MIB:              "Management Information Base" - a set
                   of parameters that  is used by SNMP
                   enabled polling devices to query
                   other SNMP enabled devices.

 NFS:              "Network File System" - A protocol
                   based on IP originally developed by
                   Sun Microsystems.

 NIC:              "Network Interface Card", also known
                   as "DNI - Desktop Network Interface". 
                   Any one of multiple add-in cards that
                   allow a microcomputer to access the
                   network system/services.

 NIC:              Alternative Definition:  Network
                   Information Center
 
 NOS:              Acronym for "Network Operating
                   System"

 Novell Netware:   Often called simply "Novell" or
                   "Netware", one of several NOS's
                   providing advanced networking
                   capabilities. 

 Protocol:         The method by which two network
                   components communicate and share
                   information.

 Relay:            A piece of equipment that is used to
                   connects LANs.
 
 RFC:              "Request For Comments" - A document
                   that describes protocols for sharing
                   information.
 
 Router:           A piece of equipment that uses a
                   protocol over and above the data-link
                   protocol to transfer traffic between
                   LANs and other network links.

 Server:           Also known as File-Server - A high-
                   powered computer used as the "home"
                   for the NOS software and associated
                   hardware.  May also access as the
                   central location for providing
                   features such as data storage and
                   printer/CD-ROM usage to people on the
                   network.

 Shielded TP:      "Shielded Twisted Pair" - A cable
                   type belonging to the twisted-pair
                   cable family, that consists of a
                   metallic shield around the twisted
                   conductors. 
 
 SMTP:             "Simple Mail Transfer Protocol" - the
                   method used in the TCP/IP family for
                   the transfer of electronic mail.
 
 SNMP:             "Simple Network Management Protocol"
                   - A specification developed for the
                   purpose of managing network hardware,
                   such as  hubs, interface cards,
                   routers, bridges, etc.
 
 TCP/IP:           "Transmission Control
                   Protocol/Internet Protocol" -
                   Actually two protocols.  Originally
                   developed for the Defense Department
                   to attach networks.

 TELNET:           A protocol used for allowing once
                   computer to remotely access another
                   computer.  Part of the TCP/IP family.

 TN3270:           An extension of the TELNET protocol. 
                   TN3270 allows users to access and
                   attach to IBM Mainframes.

 Token Ring:       A type of wiring topology that has
                   stations wired in a ring, where each
                   station passes a message, called a
                   token" sequentially down the line of
                   computers. 

 Tunnelling:       The ability to take information
                   enclosed in one type of networking
                   protocol, wrap it in another
                   protocol, move it over some distance,
                   and decode it at the other end so
                   that the receiving equipment sees
                   only the protocol used by the
                   originating equipment.

 Twisted Pair:     A cable type where the strands of
                   wire are twisted, thereby allowing
                   electronic communications that would
                   not otherwise be possible.

 T1:               A protocol for running 24 digitized
                   voice circuits through one 1.5
                   megabit/second digital channel.  T1
                   circuits can be split to provide 24
                   low-speed circuits, 1 high-speed
                   circuit, several different
                   combinations.

 VAR:              "Value Added Reseller" - A store or
                   person that you purchase products and
                   support from, instead of directly
                   from the company manufacturing the
                   software.

 VINES IP:         The specific protocol based on the IP
                   family of protocols in use by the
                   Banyan VINES NOS.
 
 X.400:            A protocol for mail and directory
                   services.

 X.500:            A protocol for mail and directory
                   services.
 
 10BASE-T:         A protocol which allows equipment to
                   be attached via twisted-pair cable.
 
