WHAT ARE THE STRENGTHS OF VINES?

So what makes VINES a better solution than other Network
Operating Systems?  To be truthful, the choice of a NOS
is dependant in large part on organization preference. 
However, VINES does have several outstanding features
that give it a leg up over the competition.  These
include Streettalk, the management of VINES, and the
Security of VINES.

STREETTALK

The naming system in VINES, known as Streettalk is the
easiest and most flexible naming convention to be found. 
Currently in its third revision, Streettalk supports a
number of features for associating a variety of data with
users all based on their network name.  This data can be
textual in nature or graphical.

Streettalk revolves around a naming process seen as:

                     ITEM@GROUP@ORGANIZATION.

The item can be a user, a file service, a printer, a
NetBios service, etc.  The group is the logical
association in which the item can be found.  The
organization is the logical association in which the
group can be found.

For example, many people, especially small sites, map
their organization to be the name of their place of
business.  An example might be DCI, if you worked at DCI
Incorporated.  A logical breakdown of groups might be
admin, for administration, secretarial for the clerical
staff, staff for general support personnel, sales for the
sales personnel, etc.  Then, each entity in the group has
a unique item name.  Consider the following examples:

                        Joe Smith@sales@DCI
                    Accounting Files@staff@DCI
                      Laser4@secretarial@DCI
                         Laser4@staff@DCI
                           Tom@admin@DCI
     
MANAGING VINES

VINES has been rated as one of the easiest networks to
manage.  This is in large part due to it's streettalk
naming system, 

VINES is managed through one easy-to-use text-based
interface.  Banyan is said to be working on a GUI
interface to the management of the network.  Almost any
type of VINES management task can be performed by typing
'MANAGE' anywhere at the DOS prompt.

Managing a User

A user is managed by defining a valid Streettalk name,
entering a description of the user, assigning a password,
assigning a nickname, and defining a login profile.  The
login profile is used to map what services on the network
are automatically given to the user when they log in. 
There is also some limited abilities of the login profile
to execute commands after the user has completed logging
in the network, via a command called POSTLOGIN.

Managing Lists

A list is simply a collection of Streettalk names.  A
list may be created to easily send electronic mail to a
large group, or to control what users get to use what
printer.  A list is mechanism that can be used to
accomplish other tasks easier.  The creation of a list is
quite simple.  Using the menus from MANAGE, simply choose
'List', provide a valid streettalk name for the list and
then define the members of the list.

Managing a service

A service is process on the network that performs some
type of task.  There are many services that VINES uses to
control security, communications, etc.  A service is also
used to control a printer, interface to mail, provide
streettalk directory assistance, etc.  The steps to
create a new service are very simple.  Using the menu
interface, select a name, add a description, select the
type of service you wish to create and select the disk on
which the service should be located.  You can start the
service as soon as you create it, and then manage the
specifics of that particular service.

For a print service, the specifics might include
authorized users, control codes for header and footer
pages on print jobs, etc.  For another type of service,
say, Streettalk Directory Assistance, you could control
what information is collected, how often it is collected,
what information is presented to users for viewing and
use, etc.

Managing a file service

A file service is a service that holds data in use by the
users on the network.  You create a file service by
specifying a name for the service, and then specifying a
disk, location where it should be placed.  Like other
services, you are given the opportunity to start the
service immediately after creating it.

Managing a Printer

Managing a printer can be done in two different ways. 
Printers can be hung off the serial port of the printer. 
This scenario only requires that you create a print
service for the printer.  VINES also features a remote
printing option, which allows you to map users to print
to any locally attached printer on a PC on the network. 
This does take a bit of memory and CPU overhead on the
workstation, and the printer must be attached to LPT1 of
the computer.  To utilize this type of printing, you have
to combine a print service and a user authorized to
accept the print data from the server.  Many sites use
"dummy-ids" that have no rights to network resources
other than the one printer they control.  These PC's can
then be located in areas close to personnel and may
eliminate the need for printers attached directly to the
server.

VINES NETWORK SECURITY

A networked computing environment requires security to be
analyzed at three levels - physical, network access, and
data access.

At the physical level, security measures must be taken to
protect computer hardware, software, and peripherals.
Network access security is necessary to safeguard users
against unauthorized access to a LAN, or to the data
available on that LAN. Finally, data access security
provides protection against unwanted destruction or
manipulation of sensitive information.

While controlling physical access to workstations can be
an effective security measure, the network operating
system can provide an additional level of control against
unwanted access to date. Here, software can be
instrumental in safeguarding access to the LAN at a
number of entry levels. For example, the software can
ensure that a user be recognized to get onto the network.
Once a user is logged in, access to applications, files,
and records can all be controlled.

At the operating system level, user identification
controls such as passwords and ID numbers can validate if
the user is authorized to be on that system. Passwords,
or any identification system, should be difficult to
guess, easy for the owner to remember, frequently
changed, and well protected.

The operating system can also allow for audit trails -
the ability to trace what has taken place on the system.
In this way users' actions can be accounted for,
monitored, and
logged.

Managers can decide which employees have network access,
and what types of information they have access to by
locking them out of particular areas of informational
access. Access Rights Lists can be used to restrict
access to applications, files and records, and can limit
users' rights to read, write, open, delete, or modify
files.

Banyan recognized the importance of network security from
the very beginning. The original design of Banyan's
network operating system, VINES, incorporated two levels
of security support. Login passwords, set by the
administrator, were made available to restrict initial
access to the system.  Access Rights Lists, set by the
system administrator, were incorporated to provide
protection for the contents of file volumes, network
services, and communications links.

Access Rights Lists are tightly integrated into Banyan's
network-wide naming system (Streettalk), providing
administrator with conventions that are consistent across
the network. Since it is integrated with Streettalk,
security is totally transparent to users. Streettalk
operates in the background, and checks to verify users'
access rights before allowing them to utilize specific
network resources.

There are two sets of access rights groupings.  The first
contains entries to control large numbers of users at a
single time.  The second set is used more for exceptions
or users or do not fit within the confines of the more
global settings.

Additionally, there are numerous types of administrative
regulation that can be used.  VINES provides the ability
(on the DOS side) to have Control, Search, Read, Write,
and Delete capabilities on directories.  Files have flags
for the Control, Execute, Read and Write capabilities. 
On the Macintosh side, there are rights for See Folders,
See Files, and Make Changes.

More recently, additional security features have been
added. The VANGuard (VINES Authentication and Network
Guardian) Service significantly increases a network
manager's ability to control access to network resources.
In addition, VANGuard is fully integrated in Streettalk's
network-wide naming Service. 

VANGuard allows administrators to select the level of
protection and the security options they want for their
organizations. Secondly, VANGuard provides the means to
centrally control access to network resources. VANGuard
includes three aspects; audit trails and reporting tools,
system-wide features, and group and individual security
features.

Audit Trails and Reporting Tools

Reports are currently available on two audit trails.  One
will list all users who log in and out of the system; the
other will track the files accessed. Reports will provide
users' names, times and dates of accesses, and locations.
Future releases will support additional trails and
reporting functions.

System-Wide Security Features

VANGuard provides tightened control over system-wide
access. Features include:
     - password encryption
     - protection against unauthorized login
     - protection from unauthorized access to network
     traffic, 
     - virtual network connections only for the purpose
     of exchanging mail. 

Specifically, these enchantments provide:

Password Encryption:  When users log into VINES, their
names and passwords are sent from the PC to the server
for verification. These passwords will now be sent across
the network in an encrypted format. This will prevent
someone from "stealing" passwords through use of a
network listening device.

Unauthorized Login Protection and Tracking:  VANGuard
will track invalid user/password attempts.  It  prevents
an intruder from accessing the network, the security
software will effectively lock the users' PC after a
limited number of attempts. All failed attempts will
automatically be recorded in logs, alerting the system
administrator that someone has tried to break into the
system.

No Session replay:  There are various types of data
scopes which, when attached to a network, can decode
traffic and later broadcast it over the LAN. Unauthorized
access could be achieved by replaying the recorded
messages even if the password and other information are
encrypted. VANGuard can prevent this by requiring all
network communication sessions to be transparently
authenticated by using a unique key that encodes time and
date information. This feature prevents replaying
sessions as a means to access the network.

Restricted Network Merger:  One of the features provided
by VINES is server-to-server communications over local
and wide-area networks.  Generally, when two servers
connect, the Streettalk naming information residing on
each server is automatically exchanged. Now
administrators can limit the exchange of naming
information to only the names of the connecting servers. 
The benefits of this feature is that making a single
server known minimizes security risks while still
allowing electronic mail messages, including file
attachments, to be exchanged.

Group and Individual Security Features

With VANGuard, system administrators will be able to
specify security attributes on either a group or
individual user basis. The attributes for both functions
are menu-selectable and include:

User ID Expiration Date:  Allows administrators to limit
access to a specified period of time. (e.g., if a company
hires a consultant for one month).

Time/Date Restrictions:  Can be used to prevent users
from accessing the system during off hours or at other
unauthorized times.

Limitations on the Number of Simultaneous Logins per
User:  Can prevent individuals from logging into multiple
PC's, creating the possibility of leaving PC's unattended
for a period of time. (Because Banyan's "virtual" network
allows users to log in on any workstation and
transparently access their own resources, they can, in
fact, log in several times). 

Restrictions on Physical Location:  Can also be used to
limit a users' access to the network by restricting the
user to a specific workstation.

Password Management Features:  Allows system
administrators to enforce password standards.
Administrators can set password length requirements,
expiration dates, and can force users to change their
passwords after they first log in. 

Dial-in Restrictions:  Allows administrators to decide
which users can have dial-in access to the network.

Profile and Password Modification Limits:  Allows
organizations to prevent users from changing their own
profile descriptions and passwords.

A VINES NETWORK

A VINES network consists of three main pieces:  The
server, the wiring and the client computer.  The server
and the client will be discussed briefly.  VINES will run
on almost any type of Wiring, including Ethernet, Token
Ring, Arcnet, and Fiber.  A specific discussion of wiring
types and their relative advantages and disadvantages is
outside the scope of this FAQ.

Server

The server is the computer that manages all the
communications between clients and other servers on the
network.  As mentioned previously, VINES can run on
Intel-based machines such as 386, 486, and 586 CPU's, as
well as a variety of other platforms.  The base operating
system for VINES is a version of UNIX, which Banyan has
heavily modified to support their needs.

Many items should be considered when buying a server. 
Disk sizes, the types of disks, disk access time, the
amount of RAM, the CPU, bus throughput, etc. are all
items that should be considered.  In an attempt to make
these selections easier on new networks, Banyan certifies
servers to work with their operating system.   These
certifications are posted in the "Hardware Compatibility
Guide."  The hardware certified for compatibility include
server platforms, network interface cards, host adaptors,
SCSI disk drives, tape drive units, Uninterruptable power
supplies, and routers.  Banyan releases a new
compatibility guide every six months.  Copies can be
obtained from Banyan or a Banyan VAR.

Clients

Almost any client computer can be hooked to any network,
including a VINES network.  It simply requires the proper
installation of a network interface card, some cabling,
and some software.  As mentioned in the previous
paragraph, network interface cards (NIC) are certified by
Banyan in the Hardware Compatibility Guide.  There are a
number of vendors, each with some various twists and
incentives to get you to buy their NIC.  In general,
there are two ways to run a client PC on a VINES network: 
via a direct driver for the card in use, or via the NDIS
protocol.

1.  Direct Driver - A direct driver is also known as a
packet driver.  Banyan writes direct drivers for many of
the vendors NICs.  Direct drivers often have the
advantage of easier setup and faster operation.  One
disadvantage is that the direct drivers will not work
with other NOS's requiring that multiple stacks be
loaded.

Usually, a direct driver simply requires the appropriate
software to be loaded in AUTOEXEC.BAT and the some
changes to be made to PCCONFIG.  PCCONFIG is the VINES
configuration program for the network card.  Settings in
PCCONFIG must be correct and match the NIC settings if
the connection is going to be established.

Depending on the card type, there may be a driver
necessary for the card to initialize properly.  This
driver should be loaded BEFORE attempting top login to
VINES.  An example line for a Cabletron E2110-X NIC is:

C:\CBLTRON2\E21PDM

Then the only thing that needs to be added for a direct
driver card is the following lines in the AUTOEXEC.BAT
file.  Do NOT type the information after the :, as it
appears for descriptive purposes only.

cd\VINES                 : change to the VINES
subdirectory
ban /nc >>NUL            : load "ban" with no-connection
csiban                   : Load the VINES direct driver
                         for the particular card
redir4                   : run the Banyan Redirector
z:\login                 : now login


2.  NDIS - NDIS stands for Network Device Independent
Specification.  It is a method of running networks and
networking software that is independent of the
manufacturer of the software.  That is it's main
advantage.  The disadvantages are that it can be
difficult to configure and depending on the NIC in
question, may be slower than a direct driver.  In
reality, though, NDIS is the future.  Banyan has already
announced that no more direct drivers will be written for
new network interface cards, and that NDIS is their
preferred connection method.  In light of that, a quick
example of and NDIS configuration is in order:


            Guide to Configuring NDIS with Banyan VINES
                    
There are three files that need adjusting to enable an
NDIS connection to a VINES network.  These files are: 
CONFIG.SYS, AUTOEXEC.BAT, and PROTOCOL.INI.  Each of
these files is shown below, along with the modifications
that need to be made.

1.  CONFIG.SYS

Your C:\CONFIG.SYS will look something like this:

device=c:\dos\himem.sys
device=c:\dos\emm386.exe x=c800-cb00 noems
device=c:\dos\ansi.sys
device= \dos\setver.exe
dos=high,umb
switches=/W
shell=c:\dos\command.com  /p /e:640
lastdrive=i
files=25
buffers=20

This next section are the NDIS specific statements and
should be added to the end
of CONFIG.SYS using your favorite editor.

device= c:\net\protman.dos /i:c:\net
device= c:\net\macwd.dos
device= c:\dis_pkt.gup

The DIS_PKT.GUP line need only be added if Packet Driver
Support is required.

"PROTMAN.DOS /i:c:net" points to the subdirectory
location of PROTOCOL.INI

The Files MACWD.DOS is LAN Card dependent, as is its
name, and can be found on the disk supplied with the LAN
Card.  Refer to the manufacturers booklet for the actual
name and any additional switches that may be required.


2.  AUTOEXEC.BAT

Using your favorite editor modify C:\AUTOEXEC.BAT to
include the following:

ban /nc >> NUL      : load "ban" with no-connection
ndisban             : load the NDIS Banyan Driver. The
                    NDDGBAN driver may be
                    : loaded instead it PACKET support is
                    required.  This is the
                    : case if you are using EBANYAN
                    TCP/IP.
netbind             : run netbind, to bind the banyan
                    driver and any other  NDIS
                    : drivers together.
redir4              : run the Banyan Redirector
arswait             : now the Address Resolution Wait
z:\login            : now login

These are just the VINES parts, and are usually loaded as
the last part of AUTOEXEC.BAT.  Do NOT type the comments
after the ":" as these are for explanation only.

3.  PROTOCOL.INI

The file PROTOCOL.INI should be in the directory
specified by PROTMAN.DOS in CONFIG.SYS (in this example
C:\NET\PROTOCOL.INI) and should be as follows.  Again, do
not type the text after the ":" as these are comments
only.

    [PROTOCOL MANAGER]   : [PROTOCOL MANAGER]
     DriverName=PROTMAN$ : The PROTMAN$ is required by
                         : PROTMAN.DOS
     Dynanic=YES         : This avoids a 67k hole in the
                         memory

    [VINES]              : [VINES]
     DriverName=ndisban$ : The DriverName=ndisban$ is
                         required by the
                         : VINES NDIS Driver (loaded in
                         : AUTOEXEC.BAT
     Bindings=NET_CARD   : Bindings = NET_CARD must match
the
                         : [NET_CARD] section, and the
bindings field
                         : in PCCONFIG

    [PKTDRV]             : [PKTDRV]
     DriverName=PKTDRV   : The [PKTDRV] section is
                         optional depending of
                         : whether you wish to use a
                         Packet Driver.
     Bindings=NET_CARD   : Bindings = NET_CARD must match
                         the [NET_CARD] section.
     IntVec=0x65         : The DriverName and IntVec
                         should match the
                         : Packet Driver setup

    [NET_CARD]           : [NET_CARD]
     DriverName=MACWD$   : This section is as defined by
the LAN Card
     IRQ=10              : Manufacturer.  The IRQ
                         information must
                         : match the Interrupt Level
                         setting in PCCONFIG.
     RAMAddress=0xc800
     IOBase=0x300
     ReceiveBufSize=1024


4.  PCCONFIG

The setting in PCCONFIG must be changed to reflect those
on PROTOCOL.INI.  This is how the above example looks for
the NDIS ethernet card.  Do not forget to change the
"Select Default Communications Driver" in the "Login
Environment Settings" menu selection.

+------------------------------------------------------+
+------------------------------------------------------+
| Network Card Settings  
+------------------------------------------------------+
 NDIS Ethernet 
+------------------------------------------------------+   
|    Specify new parameters for the controller by
|    changing the current values which are displayed
|    below. Note, be sure to change the corresponding
|    jumper settings on the controller.  
|                                                         
| Interrupt Level (2 - 15) :   10 
| PROTOCOL.INI bindings =  NET_CARD
|                                                       
| Press F10 when done; ESC to exit this screen and 
| retain the original values.                             
|_______________________________________________________
|                                                         
|_______________________________________________________


5.   REBOOT

Now reboot and your NDIS configuration should work. But
remember NDIS is a black art, and the first place to look
are the "card specific" bits of CONFIG.SYS and
PROTOCOL.INI

MULTIPLE SERVERS

One of the strength of VINES is the transparent means by
which servers communicate to each other.  The main piece
of information passed back and forth is STDA, the
Streettalk Directory Assistance.  STDA is used to
propagate directory information to every server in the
network configured to receive it, thus allowing a
"global" view of the network.  The details of STDA are
beyond the scope of this FAQ.  Suffice it to say that
STDA propagation on the network is an art in itself and a
very important tool in the VINES concept of a global
network.

The other main reason of course that servers communicate
with each other is to provide data or services to users
in another part of the network.  A user on Server A can
access a database on Server Q even if Server Q is half a
continent away, if the proper security levels are met. 
There are many different ways in which a VINES network
can link servers.  These include but are not limited to
the following:

     - Server to Server LAN - Connects servers on the
     same wiring segment.
     - Server to Server WAN - Allows groups of LANs to be
     connected into a single enterprise-wide network.
     - X.25 Server to Server - Provides connectivity over
     X.25 circuits.
     - TCP/IP Server to Server - Provides connectivity
     over TCP/IP networks.
     - SNA Server to Server - Used to connect SDLC or
     Token Ring networks to SNA networks.
     - T-1 Server to Server - Connects servers across
     high-speed digital T-1 links.
     - ISDN Server to Server - Allows servers to be
     connected across public ISDN networks.

VINES AND CONNECTIVITY

ROUTING

In order to get the most from your network, you may look
into getting connected to the Internet, the public
access, world-wide data highway.  To do that, you'll need
to implement a feature called routing on your network. 
Routing gives network users the ability to connect to
remote sites and services that are not using VINES. 
There are several types of routing that VINES can
perform.  They are described very briefly below.

1)  TCP/IP Routing -- This allows TCP/IP traffic to pass
through a VINES Network, and is also a licensing
requirement when using PC/TCP from Banyan.

Example:
         
Unix TCP/IP Host --> VINES Server --> Unix TCP/IP Host  
 
2)  IBANYAN -- FTP's PC/TCP software for Banyan.  Works
with all banyan clients, including  Ethernet, Token Ring,
Banyan Dial-in, etc.  When using IBANYAN, the client PC
encapsulates its TCP/IP traffic in VINES packets.  The
VINES IP packet passes through the necessary VINES
server(s)/nets, and then is un-encapsulated back into
pure TCP/IP and sent to TCP/IP host (and vice-versa for
packets coming back to the client).  The key is the
client always transmits VINES IP.  This has the main
advantage of the routing being controlled at the server.

3)  EBANYAN -- FTP's PC/TCP software for Banyan.  This
product is almost identical to the PC/TCP directly from
FTP, except it uses Banyans NIC card drivers instead of
packet-drivers/FTP-card-specific-drivers. EBANYAN only
works with ethernet clients -- not with VINES PC-Dialin
and Token Ring.
 
Although you need the banyan drivers loaded to use
EBANYAN, it basically allows the client to operate
independently of the VINES Server.  In the client PC
setup, you specify up to 3 default gateways -- and the PC
transmits pure TCP/IP packets directly to the destination
host.   This scenario has the advantage of reducing the
server load, and maintaining the ability of the client to
perform TCP/IP even if the server is down.

REMOTE USERS

Besides routing and inter-server connectivity, VINES can
connect remote users using a variety of techniques.  One
method called PC Dial-In uses a piece of hardware in the
server called an ICA card.  Users can dial into a modem
pool hanging off the ICA card at speeds up to 14.4 Kbps
and access the same services and data as if they were
sitting at their desktop.

VINES users can also connect to the server using X.29 and
the PC Dial-In software via X.25 circuits and ISDN
circuits.  Users are supported at data rates up to 19.2
Kbps.

REMOTE HOSTS

Using VINES communications gateway for 3270 allows a
VINES network to connect to any IBM SNA mainframe from
any PC supported on the network.  Concurrent support for
8 to 128 users is available depending on the quantity
purchased.

Using VINES ATE (Asynchronous Terminal Emulation),
network users can connect to a variety of hosts on
leased-lines, dial-up lines, and X.25 connections.

SUMMARY

By now, you've probably gotten the idea the Banyan VINES
is one of the most powerful networking environments in
the market today.  Laden with features that many other
networks don't have, VINES may be the solution to your
networking problems.  This FAQ however does not mean that
Banyan VINES is the answer to every need.  There are
problems with VINES, and not all it's users are happy
ones.  However, the same can be said of EVERY  piece of
software in existence, and VINES is by far one of the
most complicated.  

You should also known that VINES is not a latent
environment.  Banyan is actively working on the next
generation of VINES to provide even more features and
tighter integration of VINES into all types of networking
environments.

Look it over, read the literature for all networks, and
make an informed decision based on the types of support
and services you need, and the money you can afford to
pay.  Please do not order VINES solely on the information
provided in this document.

