VINES has always been supported under Windows.  There are
several options available to the administrator for
Windows setup and configuration.  In addition, there are
some fabulous tools available for administering and
monitoring your network that are Windows based.  There
are also some feature rich pure Windows GUI interfaces to
Banyan Mail.  Integrating your Windows workstations onto
your VINES network will not be a problem.

The latest iteration of Windows is known as Windows 3.11
or Windows for Workgroups (WFW).  Similar in look, feel,
and operation to the previous versions, WFW adds some
operating system enhancements as well as the big new
feature of peer-to-peer networking.

In terms of the operating system itself, Microsoft has
basically made Windows faster.  The whole Windows program
interface is a bit snappier in speed, making it almost
bearable on a run-of-the-mill 386.  With the addition of
32-bit file access, speed increases up to 25 percent on
some computers may be possible.  In some rough
benchmarking tests performed by the author, some moderate
speed increases were noted in file access from both LAN-
and PC-based programs and files.  Although small, any
speed increase in Windows is a welcome sight, making this
upgrade advisable.

Microsoft has also added several network components to
WFW.  These include the ability to share personal
resources such as disk drives, printers and other
peripherals, and common network applications such as
electronic mail, a scheduler, and faxing.  WFW also
contains some metering applications to watch how your
resources are being used.

With these new features, the installation process has
become a bit trickier, requiring the administrator to
make some choices about network support along the way. 
Although Microsoft has added networking to the base
Windows product, it only works if you are using the NDIS
protocol.  Installations  running on packet drivers will
not be able to take advantage of the networking features.

This article addresses the process of installing Windows
for Workgroups in a Banyan VINES Environment using Packet
Drivers.  The installation consists of eight steps which
are explained below.

Step 1:  SETUP

Start the SETUP.EXE program on the first floppy disk of
the WFW diskette set.

You are asked for either an express or custom setup.   In
the EXPRESS setup, Windows will automatically attempt to
configure itself for your computer system and make any
changes necessary to the AUTOEXEC.BAT and CONFIG.SYS
files.  The only item you will be required to provide
some input on is the printer you are connected to and the
port.

In the CUSTOM setup, Windows gives you complete control
over the installation process, allowing you to specify
your equipment, which Windows components to install,
which printer drivers to install, and what applications
should be set up to run underneath Windows.  The custom
setup process also gives you full control over changes
made to the AUTOEXEC.BAT and CONFIG.SYS files.

Administrators who don't like programs fooling around
with startup files will probably want to choose CUSTOM. 
As this is the method for which the most explanation is
required, the remaining steps pertain to the CUSTOM setup
procedure. 

After choosing custom, the setup program will attempt to
determine the type of equipment associated with your
computer.  Any selection can be changed by moving the
cursor keys to highlight the entry and hitting the
<ENTER> key.  A list of all possible choices will appear. 
You can make the selection you prefer and hit <ENTER>
again.  then your equipment is specified to your liking,
highlight the Accept Configuration line and press
<ENTER>.

It should be noted that there is no NETWORK line in
SETUP, which differs from previous versions of Windows. 
The entire network setup procedure is performed later.

STEP 2:  PRINTER SETUP

After disk six of the eight disk set, you'll be prompted
for what printer you'd like to use with WFW.  Microsoft
finally has drivers for the printers like the Hewlett
Packard LaserJet 4, so if you're used to your printer not
being available in previous versions, check again.  You
may be surprised.   As a side note, the list is
searchable by the first letter, so if you have a
Panasonic for example, hitting "P" takes you quickly to
the first printer that starts with the letter "P".  The
list is not searchable on anything other than the first
letter.

Once selected, you can set up the defaults specific to
your printer.  For a laser printer, this includes the
defaults for cartridge selection, printer memory, the
dpi, etc.   If the printer is a network printer, go ahead
and use CONNECT to tell it what port the printer will be
on.  It will still say LOCAL PORT for example when you
select LPT3, but later, when you install the network, it
will recognize the network designation of the printer,
e.g. (LPT3=HP4@sales@acme). 

STEP 3:  NETWORK SETUP

Once the printer selection and setup  is complete, WFW
presents the choices for Network selections .  This is an
entirely new section in the SETUP program.  An additional
twist to this setup procedure is the WFW attempts to
identify the type of network card installed in your
machine.  Knowing the specifics of the card setup is
necessary for running the WFW network applications.

There are three areas of network setup:  NETWORKS,
SHARING and DRIVERS.  If you just want to install VINES
support, follow through the NETWORKS section only.  If
you want to install both VINES and WFW support, follow
the SHARING and DRIVERS section as well.  Note again that
to use both VINES and the Windows networking, you need to
be running NDIS.

                                 NETWORKS

Under the NETWORKS option box, you make the choice of
what type of network support you'd like to have.  You
have a choice of:

- No Windows support for networks
- Install Microsoft Windows Network
- Install Microsoft Windows Network and others 
- Install only support for another network

If WFW found your network card successfully, it also
figured out that you're running VINES.  To install only
VINES support, click on the NETWORK button , and click on
the bottom button.  The text associated with this button
says "Install Windows support for the following network
only"  It will be blank before you click on it.

As soon as you press the button, the Banyan VINES 5.52(5)
will appear there.  Click on OK, and you're back at the
main network menu.  You'll notice that the SHARING and
DEVICES are grayed out now, representing the fact that
Banyan VINES is not capable of sharing local devices in
the manner implemented by Microsoft.

         SHARING - Specific to an NDIS setup

If you are setting up WFW to have a Microsoft network as
well as VINES, you can allow users to access your hard
drive and printer if you so choose.  The default to both
of these is YES.  To change them, click on SHARING, and
simply remove the X in each box by clicking on it. 

         DRIVERS - Specific to an NDIS setup

Under DRIVERS, you select the protocol to use across the
wires between your workstations.  You can actually have
several.  If you are installing WFW support as well as
VINES, the drivers selected will be shown as: 
     - Banyan VINES protocol
     - Microsoft NetBEUI protocol

You can easily alter the default setups on the network
cards and the protocols.  For instance, on many network
cards, you can change the IRQ, the I/O address, and the
base memory address.  Under the defaults for the NetBEUI
protocol, you can configure the number of Maximum
Sessions and the number of NCBS.  There is no setup to
perform under the Banyan VINES protocol.

STEP 4:  MODIFY AUTOEXEC.BAT and CONFIG.SYS

As with the previous versions of Windows, the setup
program for WFW wants to modify your startup files.  The
normal modifications the program makes are listed below.

AUTOEXEC.BAT
  - Adds C:\WINDOWS to the path
  - Adds C:\WINDOWS\SMARTDRV.EXE

CONFIG.SYS
  - Adds DEVICE=C:\WINDOWS\IFSHLP.SYS
  - Adds STACKS=9,256

If Windows doesn't recognize the interface of the hard
drives in your computer, it also add in the following
line to CONFIG.SYS.  This modification usually occurs
when your computer contains SCSI hard drives.

  - DEVICE=C:\WINDOWS\SMARTDRV.EXE /DOUBLE_BUFFER

STEP 5:  SETUP APPLICATIONS

This step is also the same as previous versions of
Windows.  The setup program allows you to search your
path and/or all accessible hard drives for applications. 
Once setup has completed loading the applications, WFW
gives you the opportunity to run a tutorial on Windows.

STEP 6:  EXIT WINDOWS

After the applications are set up and you have either
bypassed or run the tutorial, a dialog box prompts you to
either exit to DOS, or Restart Windows.   If you do not
run a third party memory manager such as Quarterdeck's
QEMM, you can simply click on the RESTART WINDOWS button
and proceed to step 7.

If you do run a memory manager such as QEMM, exit to DOS. 
To allow QEMM and Windows (any version) cooperate nicely,
you must add the following line to SYSTEM.INI in the
[386Enh] section.

SystemROMBreakPoint=false

If you already have QEMM installed on your system and in
your path, simply type the command QWINFIX from the DOS
prompt.  The SYSTEM.INI file will be updated with the
correct statement.

You may also want to add some additional lines to the
[386Enh] section such as:

EMMExclude=A000-FFFE

This line helps to prevent lockups that can occur if
Windows and some TSR programs try to access the same
memory blocks.

STEP 7:  INSTALL VINES DRIVERS

When you start Windows for the first time, you'll be
prompted by the dialog box that says the support for the
VINES network is not loaded.  By clicking on the INSTALL
button, you're telling Windows to find the appropriate
files on the server that it needs, and copy them to the
local hard drive.  

Note that there are methods of installing Windows and WFW
that leave the majority of the files on the server,
including the VINES network drivers.  The choice of
installation method should be based on the server load in
your environment, and the difficulty associated with
updating local drivers in your computing situation. 

Also note that the file "VER.DLL" contained in the
Windows subdirectory is newer than the file on the Z:
drive.  You have the option of replacing it or not.

STEP 8:  STARTING WINDOWS

The final step in installing Windows for Workgroups is
naming your computer.  When you enter Windows clean for
the first time, a dialog box entitled NETDDEx appears
that asks you for a computer name.  The box states that a
name is needed for NETDDE and CLIPSRV.  NETDDE is Dynamic
Data Exchange across workstations.  CLIPSRV is the
application that allows workstations to share information
via the ClipBook Viewer.  Simply supply any name that is
not a duplicate of another computers name in the
workgroup.

This step along with the others creates a new section in
the SYSTEM.INI file called [Network].  An example section
from a workstation running VINES only is below.  

[Network]
winnet=banyan/xx055200
multinet=nonet
FileSharing=No
PrintSharing=No
computername=donaldduck

It should be noted that the NETDDEx dialog box appears
even if you did not install the Microsoft Windows for
Workgroups network.  The only way this option will not
appear when you start WFW the first time is if you do not
have a network card installed in your machine.

That's it!  In eight simple steps, you've installed the
latest and most powerful version of Windows on your
workstation.  You might want to experiment with some of
the new features such as 32-bit file access, and the
networking abilities, if you run NDIS.  You also might
want to examine the new SYSTEM.INI file, which contains
many additional statements over Windows 3.1, and some new
sections, such as [DDEShares].

