Original author:  Michael A. Ullman)

For many years, NetWare and LAN Manager have been able to
connect printers  to their networks through Ethernet or
Token Ring.  Finally, after much anticipation from users,
similar solutions are now available for Banyan VINES
networks.

Direct connect printing solutions consist of a printer
with a network  interface and EPROM (erasable
programmable read only memory) chips containing print
server software.

The benefits of direct network connected printers are
clear. Administrators no longer have to designate PCs for
print servers, and the speed of network  connections to
the printers is measured in megabits per second rather
than  characters per second, *thus realizing the maximum
potential performance of  the printer.

Performance improvements in tests that we conducted
in-house consistently revealed a 150 to 200 percent
performance increase. We have found reliability to be
extremely high.  If a file server is rebooted, these 
products automatically reconnect themselves to the
network. 

The Technology

Vendors have taken three basic approaches in connecting
printers directly  to the network.  The first type of
product takes advantage of the MIO  (multiple
input/output) slots of Hewlett-Packard IIISi, 4, 4Si, and
1200C  printers.  The card simply plugs into the MIO slot
in the printer.  The  card is compatible with any printer
that employs HP's MIO slot  specification.

The second approach addresses non-MIO based printers
(which are the  majority of printers out there). 
Essentially, the product is a "PCPRINT  box" that
contains an Ethernet or Token Ring interface, as well as
up to  four intelligent parallel or serial connections;
different models come in  different configurations. The
parallel or serial connections come with  built-in
distance boosters of up to 1,000 feet and can be wired
using  existing two-pair telephone wire connections.

The last approach, a parallel port adapter, essentially
is a network card  and parallel port on one device that
plugs into the Centronics parallel  interface port on a
printer.  This solution is a combination of the MIO 
board and PCPRINT box solutions, except that it uses the
parallel port  rather than a special MIO slot, which
means that these devices can be  connected to any printer
with a parallel port interface.

All three kinds of products require Banyan VINES 4.x or
later and the  PCPRINT option.

Installation of each product differs in the details, but
the concept is the  same for all of them.  After
installing the hardware and connecting it to  the
network, the administrator uses MSERVICE on a network PC
to create a  print service. He selects PCPRINT as the
Destination option.  He then uses  MUSER to create a user
ID for the printer device to log in as.  The user 
profile for that ID may be empty.  The ID is only for the
device to log in  as a PCPRINT user.  Finally, the
administrator runs the configuration  software for the
product and enters the print service name and the user
ID. 
The Industry Players

Several vendors have recently announced and begun
shipping such products.  The vendors include Banyan
Systems, Digital Products, Inc. (DPI), and  Extended
Systems, Inc. (ESI).  Each vendor provides similar
strategies with  their implementations. Banyan's products
are supplied by Digital Products  as an OEM supplier.

Digital Products, Inc.

Digital Products offers two kinds of product that connect
printers to VINES  networks.  The first is called the
JETXPrint/100 (JETS100E/B) MIO board,  which connects HP
LaserJet IIISi, 4, 4Si, and 1200C printers.  The 
JETXPrint board supports twisted-pair (10BASE-T) and thin
Ethernet  (10BASE-2) connections.  Recently a Token Ring
version of the JETXPrint/100  board was added to the
