CONNECTING VINES TO THE WORLD

There's a great big world out there with billions of
bytes of information readily available.  In most cases,
your user's are going to want access to it.  Following is
a quick overview of some of the types of services that
are available or used over the Internet.

Archie:  Database servers that maintain lists of files
(by name) available for downloading via anonymous FTP
from hundreds of sites. Archie clients can search these
databases using file names or substrings.

Gopher:  Servers originally for textual information. One
gopher server can have pointers to other servers. Gopher
clients use simple menus to access this information.

Jughead:  A tool that maintains an index of menu
information from various gopher servers.

Veronica:  A service that maintains an index of titles of
gopher items and provides keyword searches of these
titles. Veronica is currently accessed through Gopher
clients.

WAIS:  (Wide-Area Information Servers). Servers that
maintain large databases of textual information that have
full-text and keyword search capabilities.  Almost 500
large databases are available world-wide. WAIS clients
can request searches by multiple keywords where results
are displayed as menu items.

WWW:  (The Web). Servers that offer hypertext menus that
may contain text (Postscript quality), sound clips,
images, and video. The Mosiac GUI client front ends are
quite spectacular.

MIME:  (Multimedia Internet Mail Extensions). Internet
e-mail support for multipart messages containing
formatted text, sound, images, video, and attachments. A
large number of UNIX and non-UNIX mailers are adding MIME
support. MIME is likely to become the defacto standard
between proprietary mail systems.

RP:  (Remote Printing).Using the Internet to send faxes
to free fax servers that service various U.S. and
international area codes.

MBone:  (Multicast Backbone), The backbone of IP sites
that support the IP multicasting protocol for
broadcasting a session from one host to many. The Mbone
is used for live audiocasts and video conferencing.

RTP:  (Real time protocol). An experimental Real-Time
Protocol designed to better handle real-time network
activities such as audiocasts and video conferencing.

sd:  A session directory program to current multimedia
events being broadcast over Mbone.

Video:  Several X Window-based UNIX programs that support
initiating and receiving slow-frame video conferences,
usually by IP multicasting over the Internet.

wb:  A UNIX program that provides a network whiteboard
for meetings



